         <abstract>
            <p>The paper describes the functional relationship of the components making up shoe-dram type brake systems for heavy duty on-highway commençai vehicles. Analysis of torque-time traces is believed to be an aid in understanding what takes place at the lining-drum interface. A contrast between theory and practice is emphasized by discussing vehicle and laboratory testing, the usage of commercial vehicles, and the empiric nature of friction. A hypothetical vehicle is used to illustrate brake engineering practice, but is restricted to load-torque balance and does not concern brake size selection.</p>
         </abstract>
